\par }{\fs20\cf0 Transmutation [Cold]
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Level:}{\fs20\cf0  Drd 2
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Components:}{\fs20\cf0  V, S, DF
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Casting Time:}{\fs20\cf0  1 standard action
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Range:}{\fs20\cf0  Close (25 ft. + 5 ft./2 levels)
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Target: }{\fs20\cf0 Metal equipment of one creature per two levels, no two of which can be more than 30 ft. apart; or 25 lb. of metal/level, none of which can be more than 30 ft. away from any of the rest
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Duration:}{\fs20\cf0  7 rounds
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Saving Throw: }{\fs20\cf0 Will negates (object)
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Spell Resistance:}{\fs20\cf0  Yes (object)
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Chill metal }{\fs20\cf0 makes metal extremely cold. Unattended, nonmagical metal gets no saving throw. Magical metal is allowed a saving throw against the spell. An item in a creature\rquote s possession uses the creature\rquote 
s saving throw bonus unless its own is higher.
\par A creature takes cold damage if its equipment is chilled. It takes full damag
e if its armor is affected or if it is holding, touching, wearing, or carrying metal weighing one-fifth of its weight. The creature takes minimum damage (1 point or 2 points; see the table) if it\rquote s not wearing metal armor and the metal that it
\rquote s carrying weighs less than one-fifth of its weight.
\par On the first round of the spell, the metal becomes chilly and uncomfortable to touch but deals no damage. The same effect also occurs on the last round of the spell\rquote s duration. During the second (and also the next-t
o-last) round, icy coldness causes pain and damage. In the third, fourth, and fifth rounds, the metal is freezing cold, causing more damage, as shown on the table below.
